Reasoning:
The lamp’s ultraviolet output is a power, i.e. an energy flow:

\[
P_{\text{UV}} = 3.00\ \text{W}=3.00\ \frac{\text{J}}{\text{s}}
\]

Each photon of wavelength \( \lambda = 280\ \text{nm}\) carries the quantum energy

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
\]

Insert the constants and convert the wavelength to metres:

\[
h = 6.626\times10^{-34}\ \text{J·s},\qquad 
c = 2.998\times10^{8}\ \text{m·s}^{-1},\qquad
\lambda = 280\ \text{nm}=280\times10^{-9}\ \text{m}
\]

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=
\frac{(6.626\times10^{-34}\ \text{J·s})(2.998\times10^{8}\ \text{m·s}^{-1})}
     {280\times10^{-9}\ \text{m}}
=7.09\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}
\]

The number of photons emitted each second is the total energy delivered per second divided by the energy of one photon:

\[
n' = \frac{P_{\text{UV}}}{E_{\text{photon}}}
    = \frac{3.00\ \text{J·s}^{-1}}
           {7.09\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}}
    = 4.23\times10^{18}\ \text{s}^{-1}
\]

Solution:
n' = E_total / E_photon = 3.00 W x 1 J s^-1 W^-1 / h c / λ = 3.00 W x 1 J s^-1 W^-1 / 6.626x10^-34 J s x 2.998x10^8 m s^-1 / 280x10^-9 m = 4.23x10^18 s^-1

Reasoning:
The incident radiation consists of photons of wavelength  

\[
\lambda = 300\ \text{nm}=3.00\times10^{-7}\ \text{m}
\]

Photon energy is obtained from Planck’s relation  

\[
E_{\text{ph}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
\]

with \(h=6.626\times10^{-34}\ {\rm J\,s}\) and \(c=2.998\times10^{8}\ {\rm m/s}\):

\[
E_{\text{ph}}=\frac{(6.626\times10^{-34})(2.998\times10^{8})}{3.00\times10^{-7}}
          = 6.62\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}
\]

The work function of potassium is  

\[
\phi = 2.40\ {\rm eV}=2.40(1.602\times10^{-19})\ {\rm J}=3.84\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}
\]

Maximum kinetic energy of an emitted electron follows from the photo‑electric equation  

\[
K_{\max}=E_{\text{ph}}-\phi
        =6.62\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}-3.84\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}
        =2.77\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}
\]

From \(K_{\max}=\tfrac12 m_{e}v^{2}\) (with electron mass \(m_{e}=9.109\times10^{-31}\ {\rm kg}\)) the speed of a photo‑electron is  

\[
v=\sqrt{\frac{2K_{\max}}{m_{e}}}
  =\sqrt{\frac{2(2.77\times10^{-19})}{9.109\times10^{-31}}}
  =7.8\times10^{5}\ \text{m s}^{-1}
\]

The total energy absorbed by the potassium surface is  

\[
E_{\text{tot}}=3.25\times10^{-3}\ {\rm J}
\]

If each photon can liberate at most one electron, the maximum number of electrons emitted equals the total absorbed energy divided by the energy per photon:

\[
n=\frac{E_{\text{tot}}}{E_{\text{ph}}}
  =\frac{3.25\times10^{-3}}{6.62\times10^{-19}}
  =4.9\times10^{15}\ \text{electrons}
\]

